<TITLE> CHT will be developed keeping culture, nature intact: Barua </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 17(bdnews24.com)  Industries minister Dilip Barua has said the government will industrialise Chittagong Hill Tracts without affecting its rich culture and nature. "We will cooperate as part of a comprehensive plan to industrialise the country," he told bdnews24.com after a meeting with an eight-member delegation of the international commission on CHT Tuesday. "It is necessary to include the subject in the new industrial policy for development of small and medium industries with the support of the government." The co-chair of the commission, Sultana Kamal, told bdnews24.com they told the government to maintain natural balance to industrialise the Chittagong Hill Tracts. "We also asked them to consider increasing herbal colour instead of chemical colour in the traditional garment sector of CHT." She stressed on the need for discussion with local people about industrialisation. "We also told the minister about the possibility of the use of solar power or any other alternative source of power." Commission member Shapan Adnan said, "Fruits in the hill tracts cannot be properly marketed. So, we told the government to help set up food processing plants and assist in their marketing as well. Barua said, "Protection is needed for development of textiles, fruits, small and agriculture-based industries there." On the alternative source of power, the minister said, it was a matter for the energy ministry to decide. Among others present in the meeting were Lord Eric Avebury, co-chair of the international commission on Chittagong Hill Tracts, and commission member Meghna Guhathakurata an
